#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
update_meta_groups

Refreshes the "META PACKAGE(S)" and "PACKAGE GROUP(S)" columns of a package
TSV file using ONLY the local pacman database -- i.e. what's actually
installed on this machine right now. Leaves everything else (package
names, PURPOSE text, row order) untouched.

MUST be run on an Arch Linux machine (panther / tulkun) with pacman and
expac available (`sudo pacman -S expac` if you don't have it).

GROUPS
------
    pacman -Qegq
-Q (local/installed db), -e (explicitly installed only -- skips packages
that are only present as someone else's dependency), -g (group
membership). This only reflects packages genuinely on this machine, which
correctly includes AUR packages (their group tags live in the local
package metadata) -- unlike `pacman -Sg`, which only knows about
official-repo declarations and is blind to AUR entirely.

METAPACKAGES
------------
For each metapackage (base, base-devel, qemu-base, ...):
    expac -S %E <metapackage>
lists everything it currently declares as a dependency, per the sync db.
That declared list is then intersected with your actual installed set
(`pacman -Qq`) -- a dependency that's been removed from your system won't
get tagged, per your note that some declared deps may not exist locally.

VIRTUAL / "PROVIDES" DEPENDENCIES
----------------------------------
Some metapackages declare a dependency on a *virtual* name rather than a
real package -- e.g. `posix` depends on `awk` and `sh`, but no package is
literally named that. `gawk` and `bash` satisfy those names by declaring
`Provides: awk` / `Provides: sh` respectively, and pacman resolves this
at install time. A plain string match against `pacman -Qq` misses this
entirely (there's no package called "awk" to find), so such dependencies
would silently go untagged.

To catch these, every installed package's own `Provides` field is read
via `pacman -Qi` and inverted into {virtual_name: {real_pkg, ...}}. When
a metapackage's declared dependency isn't a literal installed package
name, that map is checked as a fallback, and the *real* package(s)
providing that virtual name get tagged instead -- never the virtual name
itself, since it has no row of its own in the TSV.

Rows for TSV packages that AREN'T currently installed are left completely
untouched (not blanked) -- there's no reliable local data for them, so
guessing would risk erasing previously-correct classification.

Usage:
    ./update_meta_groups package-lists/pkgs-from-official.tsv
        -> writes pkgs-from-official.updated.tsv, prints a diff to stderr

    ./update_meta_groups package-lists/pkgs-from-official.tsv --in-place
        -> overwrites the input file directly

    ./update_meta_groups package-lists/pkgs-from-official.tsv \\
        --metapackages base,base-devel,qemu-base,qemu-desktop,qemu-full
        -> override which metapackages to check membership against
"""

import argparse
import os
import re
import subprocess
import sys
from pathlib import Path

